ssance elites and Greenwich Village bohemians. An émigré in Paris, she fell in with the Left Bank avant garde, befriending Antonin Artaud, Man Ray, and Pablo Picasso. Next, she took up residence as a journalist in Barcelona during the Spanish Civil War and witnessed firsthand the growing menace of fascism. In 1940, as the Nazi panzers closed in on Paris, Reynolds spent the final days before the French capitulation as a Red Cross nurse, afterward making a mad dash for Lisbon to escape on the last ship departing Europe. In prose that perfectly captures the globetrotting nonchalance of its author, American Cocktail presents a stimulating, unforgettable self-portrait of a truly extraordinary woman.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAfrican American psychologists -- Biography. 0aAfrican American psychologistsvBiography. 0aAfrican American women -- Biography. 0aAfrican American women entertainers -- Biography. 0aAfrican American women entertainersvBiography. 0aAfrican American womenvBiography. 0aMotion picture actors and actresses -- United States -- Biography. 0aMotion picture actors and actresseszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aReynolds, Anita Thompson Dickinson, -- 1901-1980. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Personal Memoirs.2bisacsh1 aHutchinson, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutchinson, George, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMiller, Howard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilliams, Patricia J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilliams, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe G